<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-688-008  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 688 008.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 30 1990 v7 n30 p50(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Workstation-based software to ease modem sharing. (FreshTechnology Group introduces Modem Assist modem sharing package)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zimmerman, Michael R.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fresh Technology Group Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Modem Assist (Communications software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Communications softwareProduct IntroductionModemsResource SharingLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Michael R. ZimmermanandM;Adding to its family of LAN enhancement products, Fresh Technology Groupplans to ship next week a new modem-sharing package that lets network usersaccess modems based anywhere on a network, company officials said.andM;Called Modem Assist, the new software will enable users on a Novell NetWareor NetBIOS LAN to share modems installed on network workstations, accordingto Richard Girardo, director of product marketing at Fresh Technology.andM;Because it runs on network workstations, Modem Assist serves as analternative to typical modem-sharing applications that require dedicatedcommunications servers, he said.andM;The DOS-based software performs its communications and modem-sharing tasks asa terminate-and-stay-resident program, making all remote transmissionstransparent to the workstation user, said Girardo.andM;Modem Assist works with a variety of communications programs, such as DigitalCommunications Associates Inc.'s Crosstalk Mk.4 and Datastorm TechnologiesInc.'s Procomm Plus, he said.andP;  In addition, it includes a proprietarycommunications program.andM;Modem Assist will be priced at $495 for a package that supports as many asfive modems, and $995 for one that works with between six and 20 modems,according to Girardo.andM;Fresh Technology is located in Gilbert, Ariz., and can be reached at (602)497-4200.andO;</TEXT></DOC>